{{other uses|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (disambiguation)}}

[[Image:Slc mormon tempel.jpg|thumb|right|235px|The [[Salt Lake Temple]] of '''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints''' is the largest attraction in the city's [[Temple Square]].]]

'''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints''', widely known as the '''LDS Church''' or the '''Mormon Church''', is the largest and most well-known [[Religious denomination|denomination]] originating from the [[Latter Day Saint movement]] (a group of [[church]]es and adherents who follow the teachings of [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]]). The church is headquartered in [[Salt Lake City, Utah|Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]] and has established churches and [[temple (Latter Day Saints)|temples]] worldwide, self-reporting nearly 13 million members on its rolls.<ref name="currentmembership">[http://www.lds.org/ldsnewsroom/v/index.jsp?vgnextoid=d10511154963d010VgnVCM1000004e94610aRCRD Statistical Information], Retrieved May 2, 2007</ref>

Adherents to the church (usually called ''[[Mormon]]s'', ''Latter-day Saints'' or ''LDS'') believe that [[Jesus]] leads their church via [[revelation]] given to the [[President of the Church (Latter Day Saints)|President of the Church]], whom they consider to be a [[prophet]]. They count themselves as [[Christian]]s, but do not consider themselves part of the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Orthodox Christianity|Orthodox]], or [[Protestantism|Protestant]] traditions. Instead, they believe that the church is a [[restoration (Latter Day Saints)|restoration]] of [[1st century]] [[Christianity]]. They believe in the divine authority of the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]], but have additional [[book]]s in their [[Biblical canon|scriptural canon]]: the ''[[Book of Mormon]]'', the ''[[Doctrine and Covenants]]'', and the ''[[Pearl of Great Price (Latter Day Saints)|Pearl of Great Price]]''.

Historically, the church has distinguished itself from traditional Christian denominations by its practice of [[plural marriage|polygamy]] (discontinued beginning in 1890) and by its other unique [[doctrine]]s and practices such as the [[Endowment (Latter Day Saints)|Endowment]], [[baptism for the dead]], and its views on the [[Godhead (Latter Day Saints)|Godhead]]. The church teaches that it is "the only true and living church upon the face of the whole earth",<ref>{{lds|D&C|dc|1|30}}</ref> but it has cooperated with other religious organizations in promoting humanitarian and moral causes.

== History ==
[[Image:Joseph Smith Jr bronze bust Conference Center.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bust of [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]]]]
{{main|History of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints}}
The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints is the largest church that claims to be a continuation of the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Christ]], founded by [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]] on [[April 6]] [[1830]] in either the [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]]–[[Palmyra (town), New York|Palmyra]] area or [[Fayette, New York]].<!--

FOOTNOTE--><ref>The majority of witnesses say the church was organized [[April 6]] [[1830]] in the log home of Joseph Smith, Sr. in the [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]] area, followed by a meeting the next Sunday in nearby [[Fayette, New York|Fayette]] at the home of [[Peter Whitmer, Sr.]] Nevertheless, one of Smith's histories and a later reminiscence by [[David Whitmer]] say the church was organized at the Whitmer home in Fayette. See [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)]]. The Church refers to Fayette as the place of organization in all its official [[publication]]s.</ref><!--

--> Joseph Smith established this early church soon after publishing the ''[[Book of Mormon]]''. The church rapidly gained a large following who viewed Smith as a [[prophet]].  The rapid growth of Smith's following was attributed by some to the convincing power of the Book of Mormon, which Smith said that he translated from a book of [[golden plates]], buried near his home in a place shown him by [[Moroni (prophet)|an angel]].<ref name="JSTestimony">[http://lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=69f9307e3584b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 Joseph Smith's Testimony]</ref>

In late 1830, Smith envisioned a [[Zion (Latter Day Saints)|"city of Zion"]] in [[Native Americans|Native American]] lands near [[Independence, Missouri]]. In October 1830 he sent his second-in-command [[Oliver Cowdery]] and others on a [[mission]] to the area.<ref>{{lds|D&C|dc|32}}</ref> Passing through [[Kirtland, Ohio]], the missionaries converted a congregation of [[Disciples of Christ]] led by [[Sidney Rigdon]], and in 1831, Smith decided to temporarily move his followers to Kirtland until the [[Missouri]] area could be colonized. The church headquarters remained in Kirtland from 1831 to 1838; meanwhile, the church built [[Kirtland Temple|its first temple]] and grew in size.

On [[July 20]], [[1831]] Smith circulated a written revelation that [[Independence, Missouri]] was to be the center place for the city of Zion.<ref>{{lds|D&C|dc|57|1-3}}</ref> Though many of Smith's followers attempted to colonize Missouri throughout the 1830s, and Smith himself moved there in 1838, the church faced political and military opposition by other Missouri settlers. After a series of raids on Mormon settlements, the church formed its own militia and the [[Mormon War]] of 1838 ensued, culminating in the religion being expelled from the state under an [[Extermination Order]] signed by [[Lilburn W. Boggs|the governor of Missouri]]. The church then established its new headquarters in [[Nauvoo, Illinois]], a city they built on drained swampland by the [[Mississippi River]], where Joseph Smith Jr. served as mayor. There, the church built a [[Nauvoo Temple|new temple]], and thrived until Smith and his brother Hyrum, whom most agree would have been Joseph's successor, were [[death of Joseph Smith, Jr.|killed by a mob]] in 1844. They were awaiting trial for their decision to destroy a [[Nauvoo Expositor|local newspaper]] that said Smith was practicing a form of [[polygamy]] and that he intended to establish himself as a theocratic king. Joseph Smith Jr., at the time, was a minor candidate for [[President of the United States]].

After Joseph and Hyrum's death, some church leaders campaigned to lead the church during a time known as the [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|Succession Crisis]]. The majority of adherents voted to accept the succession claims presented by the [[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles]], led by [[Brigham Young]]. After continued difficulties in Illinois, Brigham Young left Nauvoo in 1846, and led his followers (called the [[Mormon pioneers]] during this period) to what later became [[Utah]] (then part of [[Mexico]]), and began to colonize the area with numerous small cities.

In Utah, Young incorporated The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints as a legal entity under the laws of the [[Territory of Utah]]. He initially governed his followers as a [[theocracy|theocratic]] leader, and openly encouraged the practice of [[plural marriage]], which Joseph Smith had tried to keep secret. When word of the practice got back to [[Washington, D.C.]], the United States sent federal troops there in 1857, [[Utah War|deposed Young]], and replaced him with [[Alfred Cumming (governor)|a non-Mormon territorial governor]], though Young still wielded significant political power as [[President of the Church (Latter Day Saints)|President of the Church]]. Young was followed by other powerful leaders, who were defiant in the face of U.S. efforts to outlaw polygamous marriages in the territory. Political and legal wrangling over the polygamy issue escalated until 1890, when church president [[Wilford Woodruff]] issued a [[1890 Manifesto|Manifesto]] officially suspending the practice.<ref>{{lds|Official Declaration —|od|1}}</ref> Church relations with the United States markedly improved after 1890, and especially after 1904, when church president [[Joseph F. Smith]] [[Reed Smoot hearings|disavowed polygamy]] before the [[United States Congress]] and issued a "Second Manifesto" calling for all polygamous marriages in the church to cease. Since about the 1930s, the church has adopted a policy of [[excommunication|excommunicating]] its members found practicing polygamy.

During the [[20th century]], the church experienced a period of exponential growth, due to a high birth rate and extensive [[proselytism]].{{Fact|date=May 2007}} In 1978, after years of internal discussion within the church hierarchy, the church ended its longtime practices of [[Blacks and Mormonism|not allowing blacks to hold the priesthood]] and prohibiting their participation in temple ceremonies thought necessary for the highest degree of salvation. Since the 1990s, the church's growth rate has no longer been exponential, but the church continues to gain about 300,000 new members per year.{{Fact|date=May 2007}} 

===Historical positions on moral and political issues===
The church has played a prominent role in political matters, including opposition to the repeal of [[Prohibition in the United States]],{{Fact|date=May 2007}} opposition to [[LGM-118A Peacekeeper|MX (Peacekeeper) missile]] bases in Utah and Nevada,<ref>“[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=b0d6fc3157a6b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 First Presidency Statement on Basing of MX Missile]”, ''Ensign'', June 1981, 76.</ref> opposing the [[Equal Rights Amendment]],<ref>[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=f8a4615b01a6b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 “The Church and the Proposed Equal Rights Amendment: A Moral Issue”], ''Ensign'', Mar. 1980, insert.</ref> opposing legalized [[gambling]],<ref>[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=4ace94bf3938b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 “Church’s Stand against Gambling]”, ''Ensign'', Mar. 1992, 74.</ref> support of bans on [[same-sex marriage]],<!--

